04362nam a22006015i 9780520959965DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209599657 a10.1525/97805209599652doi  a(DE-B1597)519408  a(OCoLC)907067934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a3312231 aOrdonez, Juan Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJornalero :bBeing a Day Laborer in the USA /cJuan Thomas Ordonez. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Series in Public Anthropology ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Brief Note on Language -- tIntroduction -- t1. La Parada de Berkeley -- t2. Friendship and the Inner Workings of Day Labor -- t3. Abuse and the Absurd Bureaucracy of Small Things -- t4. The "Other" among Others -- t5. Bittersweet Nostalgia, Sexuality, and the Body at Risk -- t6. Belonging -- t7. Terror and the May Migra Panic -- tConclusions -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United States has seen a dramatic rise in the number of informal day labor sites in the last two decades. Typically frequented by Latin American men (mostly "undocumented" immigrants), these sites constitute an important source of unskilled manual labor. Despite day laborers' ubiquitous presence in urban areas, however, their very existence is overlooked in much of the research on immigration. While standing in plain view, these jornaleros live and work in a precarious environment: as they try to make enough money to send home, they are at the mercy of unscrupulous employers, doing dangerous and underpaid work, and, ultimately, experiencing great threats to their identities and social roles as men. Juan Thomas Ordóñez spent two years on an informal labor site in the San Francisco Bay Area, documenting the harsh lives led by some of these men during the worst economic crisis that the United States has seen in decades. He earned a perspective on the immigrant experience based on close relationships with a cohort of men who grappled with constant competition, stress, and loneliness. Both eye-opening and heartbreaking, the book offers a unique perspective on how the informal economy of undocumented labor truly functions in American society.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aDay laborersxCaliforniaxBerkeley. 0aDay laborerszCaliforniazBerkeley. 0aForeign workers, Latin AmericanxCaliforniaxBerkeley. 0aForeign workers, Latin AmericanzCaliforniazBerkeley. 0aIllegal aliensxEmploymentxCaliforniaxBerkeleyxCaliforniaxBerkeley. 0aIllegal aliensxEmploymentzCaliforniazBerkeley. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520959965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520959965.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles